You can do this (the long way) using a **for** loop and several **if** statements. You definitely want to use the [Character.isDigit()](https://www.javatpoint.com/post/java-character-isdigit-method) method within your **if** statement conditions.

You need to iterate through the SSN string supplied by the User one character at a time so use of the [String.charAt()](https://www.tutorialspoint.com/java/java_string_charat.htm) method is important here as well. Here is one way you might go about it:

    Scanner input = new Scanner(System.in);
    String inputSSN = &quot;&quot;;
        
    while (inputSSN.equals(&quot;&quot;)) {
        System.out.print(&quot;Enter a Social Security Number: --&gt; &quot;);
        inputSSN = input.nextLine();

        // Validate SSN...
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; inputSSN.length(); i++) {
            // Validate the first set of 3 digits
            if (i &gt;= 0 &amp;&amp; i &lt;= 2) {
                if (!Character.isDigit(inputSSN.charAt(i))) {
                    inputSSN = &quot;&quot;;
                    break;
                }
                continue;
            }

            // Validate the first hyphen
            if (i == 3 &amp;&amp; inputSSN.charAt(i) != &#39;-&#39;) {
                inputSSN = &quot;&quot;;
                break;
            }

            // Validate the second set of 2 digits
            if (i &gt;= 4 &amp;&amp; i &lt;= 5) {
                if (!Character.isDigit(inputSSN.charAt(i))) {
                    inputSSN = &quot;&quot;;
                    break;
                }
                continue;
            }

            // Validate the second hyphen
            if (i == 6 &amp;&amp; inputSSN.charAt(i) != &#39;-&#39;) {
                inputSSN = &quot;&quot;;
                break;
            }

            // Validate the third set of 4 digits
            if (i &gt;= 7 &amp;&amp; i &lt;= 10) {
                if (!Character.isDigit(inputSSN.charAt(i))) {
                    inputSSN = &quot;&quot;;
                    break;
                }
            }
        }

        // Validate that the SSN is the right length
        if (inputSSN.length() != 11) {
            System.out.println(&quot;Invalid Social Security Number!&quot; + System.lineSeparator());
            inputSSN = &quot;&quot;;
        }
    }
        
    System.out.println(inputSSN + &quot; is a valid Social Security Number.&quot;);

